                           <quote xml:lang="gez">
                              <locus target="#116va">116va</locus>: &lt;...&gt;፡ መጽሐፍ፡ ዘወሀበቶ፡ ለአቡነ፡
                              አረጋዊ፡ ወለተ፡ ሥላሴ፡ ስመ፡ አቡሃ፡ ገብረ፡ ክርስቶስ፡ ስመ፡ እኁኀ፡ ገብረ፡ ሥላሴ፡ ስመ፡ እማ፡ ወለተ፡
                              ማርያም፡ ስመ፡ እኅታ፡ ወለተ፡ መድኅን፡ ወለተ፡ ሚካኤል፡ ወለተ፡ ክርስቶስ፡ ከመ፡ ይኵኖሙ፡ ለኵሎሙ፡
                              አዝማዲሃ፡ መርሃ፡ በመንግሥተ፡ ሰማያት፡ ለዝ፡ መጽሐፍ፡ ዘሠረቆ…</quote>
                           <quote xml:lang="en"/>
                           <note> The note is written in the main hand but with a thinner pen nib.
                              It states that Walatta Śǝllāse donated the Ms. to the monastery of
                              ʾAbuna ʾAragāwi. Subsequently, her family members are mentioned: her
                              father Gabra Krǝstos, her brother Gabra Śǝllāse, her mother Walatta
                              Māryām and her sisters Walatta Madḫǝn, Walatta Mikāʾel and Walatta
                              Krǝstos. </note>
                        </item>
                        <item xml:id="a2">
                           <locus target="#116vb">f. 116vb</locus>
                           <desc>: Acquisition note.</desc>
                           <quote xml:lang="gez">
                              <locus target="#116vb">f. 116vb</locus>: ፵፬፲፱፻፵፬[sic]፡ ዓመተ፡ ምህረት፡ ዘመነ፡
                              ዮሐንስ። እቃቤት፡ አባ፡ ገብረሥላሴ፡ ገብረ፡ ጻድቅ፡ ቄሰገዝ[sic]፡ ተክለ፡ ሃይማ{ኖ}ት፡ ገብዝ[sic]፡
                              ገብዝ[sic]፡ ገብረ፡ ማርያም። ወለተ፡ ስላሴ፡ ወለተ፡ ክርቶስ[sic]፡ የገባ፡ መጽሃፍ፡ ድርሳን፡
                              ማህያዊ&lt;…&gt;</quote>
                           <quote xml:lang="en"/> The note is written in Amharic, in a mediocre
                           hand. It states that the Ms. was obtained in 1944 year of mercy (= 1951/2
                           A.D.) in the year of John when ʾabbā<note> Gabra Śǝllāse Gabra Ṣādǝq was
                              in charge of the storehouse and Gabra Māryām was qesa gabaz of the
                              church. Subsequently, the donor Walatta Śǝllāse and her sister Walatta
                              Krǝstos are mentioned. </note>
                        </item>
